---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "2-3 Year Milestones: Development Checklist",
  "description": "Developmental milestones for 2-3 year olds. Physical, cognitive, language, and social-emotional milestones from CDC guidelines.",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "AgeExpectations"
  }
};

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What milestones should a 2-year-old achieve?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "At 2, most children can run, say 50+ words, combine two words, engage in pretend play, and show defiant behavior. The CDC milestone checklist provides details."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How many words should a 3-year-old say?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Most 3-year-olds have a vocabulary of 200+ words and speak in 3-4 word sentences. They should be mostly understandable to strangers."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When do children start playing with others?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Parallel play (playing alongside but not with others) starts around 2. Cooperative play with sharing develops between 3-4 years."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<BaseLayout title="2-3 Year Milestones: Development Checklist" description="Complete developmental milestones checklist for 2-3 year olds. Physical, cognitive, language, and social milestones from CDC guidelines." schema={schema} pageType="Article">
  <article class="article">
    <header class="article-header">
      <h1>2-3 Year Milestones: Development Checklist</h1>
      <p class="article-meta">Ages 24-36 months · Updated March 2026</p>
    </header>

    <div class="topic-nav">
      <a href="/ages/2-3-years/">Overview</a>
      <a href="/ages/2-3-years/milestones/">Milestones</a>
      <a href="/ages/2-3-years/sleep/">Sleep</a>
      <a href="/ages/2-3-years/behavior/">Behavior</a>
      <a href="/ages/2-3-years/language/">Language</a>
      <a href="/ages/2-3-years/feeding/">Feeding</a>
    </div>

    <div class="article-content">
      <p>Between ages 2 and 3, your child transforms from a baby into a little person with preferences, opinions, and a rapidly expanding vocabulary. This guide covers what developmental milestones to expect, based on CDC and AAP guidelines.</p>

      <h2>24 Month Milestones (2 Years)</h2>
      
      <h3>Physical/Motor</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Walks well, runs (more steady)</li>
        <li>Kicks a ball</li>
        <li>Climbs well on playground equipment</li>
        <li>Goes up and down stairs with help</li>
        <li>Stacks 4-6 blocks</li>
        <li>Uses spoon and fork</li>
        <li> Scribbles in circles</li>
        <li>Begins to dress/undress with help</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Language/Communication</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Vocabulary of 50+ words</li>
        <li>Combines two words ("more milk," "daddy go")</li>
        <li>Points to named objects</li>
        <li>Follows simple instructions</li>
        <li>About 50% understandable to strangers</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Cognitive</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Engages in pretend play</li>
        <li>Finds hidden objects easily</li>
        <li>Sorts shapes and colors</li>
        <li>Completes sentences in familiar books</li>
        <li>Follows 2-step instructions</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Social/Emotional</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Plays alongside other children (parallel play)</li>
        <li>Shows defiant behavior (the "no" phase)</li>
        <li>Shows affection to familiar people</li>
        <li>Has temper tantrums</li>
        <li>Imitates others, especially adults</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>30 Month Milestones (2.5 Years)</h2>
      
      <h3>Physical/Motor</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Jumps with both feet</li>
        <li>Stands on tiptoes</li>
        <li>Kicks a ball forward</li>
        <li>Uses hands to twist/turn objects</li>
        <li>Stacks 8-10 blocks</li>
        <li>Draws vertical lines</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Language/Communication</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Vocabulary of 100+ words</li>
        <li>Uses 2-3 word sentences</li>
        <li>Asks "what" and "where" questions</li>
        <li>Points to body parts when asked</li>
        <li>About 60-70% understandable</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Cognitive</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Sorts by color and shape</li>
        <li>Completes simple puzzles</li>
        <li>Understands "same" and "different"</li>
        <li>Follows 2-3 step instructions</li>
        <li>Knows basic colors</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Social/Emotional</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Shows jealousy toward siblings</li>
        <li>Plays make-believe with toys</li>
        <li>Shows pride in accomplishments</li>
        <li>May have imaginary playmates</li>
        <li>Beginning to take turns (with help)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>36 Month Milestones (3 Years)</h2>
      
      <h3>Physical/Motor</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Climbs well</li>
        <li>Runs well, can start/stop</li>
        <li>Pedals tricycle</li>
        <li>Jumps forward</li>
        <li>Walks up stairs alternating feet</li>
        <li>Stacks 10+ blocks</li>
        <li>Draws circles and squares</li>
        <li>Uses toilet independently</li>
        <li>Dresses self (with help for buttons)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Language/Communication</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Vocabulary of 200+ words</li>
        <li>Speaks in 3-4 word sentences</li>
        <li>Asks "why" questions</li>
        <li>75% understandable to strangers</li>
        <li>Can tell stories</li>
        <li>Sings songs from memory</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Cognitive</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Engages in elaborate pretend play</li>
        <li>Sorts objects by category</li>
        <li>Counts objects (doesn't understand quantity)</li>
        <li>Understands "same" and "different"</li>
        <li>Completes 3-4 piece puzzles</li>
        <li>Understands taking turns</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Social/Emotional</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Plays cooperatively with other children</li>
        <li>Takes turns (with reminders)</li>
        <li>Shows empathy when others are upset</li>
        <li>Separates from parents more easily</li>
        <li>Expresses wide range of emotions</li>
        <li>Seeks approval from adults</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Red Flags: When to Be Concerned</h2>
      <p>Talk to your pediatrician if your child:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Has fewer than 50 words at 2 years</li>
        <li>No two-word phrases by 2 years</li>
        <li>Doesn't respond to their name</li>
        <li>Doesn't make eye contact</li>
        <li>Not walking well by 2 years</li>
        <li>No pretend play by 2.5 years</li>
        <li>Loses previously acquired skills</li>
        <li>Limited interest in other children</li>
        <li>Doesn't follow simple instructions</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Supporting Your Child's Development</h2>
      <p>You don't need expensive toys — these simple activities help:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Read daily:</strong> Builds vocabulary and attention</li>
        <li><strong>Play together:</strong> Follow their lead</li>
        <li><strong>Talk lots:</strong> Narrate your day</li>
        <li><strong>Encourage independence:</strong> Let them try things</li>
        <li><strong>Limit screen time:</strong> Interactive play is better</li>
        <li><strong>Provide safe exploration:</strong> Let them climb, explore</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Is This Normal? — Common Questions</h2>
        
        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">My child isn't talking much at 2. Should I worry?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">A 50+ word vocabulary and two-word combinations are expected at 2. Some children talk more, some less. If your child has fewer than 50 words or isn't combining words, talk to your pediatrician.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">When will my child play with other kids?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Parallel play (playing beside other children) is normal at 2. Cooperative play with actual interaction typically develops between 3-4 years. Some children need more time.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">Should my 3-year-old be able to share?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">True sharing — understanding others' feelings about giving up a toy — develops around 3-4 years. Younger toddlers don't have this cognitive ability yet. Turn-taking is more realistic.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">My child still uses diapers. Is this normal?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Potty training typically happens between 18 months and 3-4 years. Many perfectly healthy children aren't fully trained until 3-4. Daytime training usually precedes nighttime control.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
